The chord length for a step \( k \) is \( 2 \sin(\pi k / 7) \). The sum of the 4th powers of these lengths is given by: \[ 7 \left[ (2 \sin(\pi/7))^4 + (2 \sin(2\pi/7))^4 + (2 \sin(3\pi/7))^4 \right] \] This simplifies to: \[ 112 \left[ \sin^4(\pi/7) + \sin^4(2\pi/7) + \sin^4(3\pi/7) \right] \] Using the trigonometric identity for \(\sin^4(x)\): \[ \sin^4(x) = \frac{3 - 4\cos(2x) + \cos(4x)}{8} \] We convert the sum of \(\sin^4\) terms into a sum involving cosines: \[ \sin^4(\pi/7) + \sin^4(2\pi/7) + \sin^4(3\pi/7) = \frac{1}{8} \left[ 9 - 4 \sum_{k=1}^3 \cos(2k\pi/7) + \sum_{k=1}^3 \cos(4k\pi/7) \right] \] We use the known values of the sums of cosines: \[ \sum_{k=1}^3 \cos(2k\pi/7) = -\frac{1}{2} \quad \text{and} \quad \sum_{k=1}^3 \cos(4k\pi/7) = -\frac{1}{2} \] Substituting these values, we get: \[ \sin^4(\pi/7) + \sin^4(2\pi/7) + \sin^4(3\pi/7) = \frac{1}{8} \left[ 9 - 4(-\frac{1}{2}) + (-\frac{1}{2}) \right] = \frac{21}{16} \] Thus, the total sum is: \[ 112 \times \frac{21}{16} = 147 \] Finally, the remainder when 147 is divided by 100 is: \[ \boxed{47} \]
